POD1000000010_S0000188	And I remember in my early 20s thinking, that's absurd.
POD1000000010_S0000189	You should totally tell children to apologize to each other.
POD1000000010_S0000190	The problem Jen found out with forced apologies is that they're usually pretty worthless.
POD1000000010_S0000191	Sorry.
POD1000000010_S0000192	and they don't even realize that they're supposed to mean it or feel it.
POD1000000010_S0000193	Yeah, so Tom Lacona and Jen Cutler both told us instead of focusing on kids parroting the words, sorry,
POD1000000010_S0000194	we should help them really take the other person's perspective. And this is important, repair the harm done.
POD1000000010_S0000195	Yeah, and this is a great tip.
POD1000000010_S0000196	Jen says you can actually take a moment like this
POD1000000010_S0000197	and direct one child to look at the other child's face and posture
POD1000000010_S0000198	And this helps them learn how to read feelings.
POD1000000010_S0000199	So it's really about more conversations and about looking at emotions and emotion knowledge and looking at faces to see how your actions affect other people.
