POD1000000014_S0000006	Peter Tyndall is a big beast of the ombudsman world. He's a Dubliner.
POD1000000014_S0000007	He's now Ombudsman for Ireland, having recently been reappointed to serve a second term.
POD1000000014_S0000008	He has a long association with Wales where he occupied a variety of senior positions in housing and social care.
POD1000000014_S0000009	He then became public service ombudsman for Wales between 2008 and 2013.
POD1000000014_S0000010	He's been chairman of the British and Irish Ombudsman Association for two years and currently he's the president of the World Board of the International Ombudsman Institute for the last four years.
POD1000000014_S0000011	Peter, you're extremely welcome. Thank you for being with us.
POD1000000014_S0000012	Thank you, Rob. Very glad to be here.
POD1000000014_S0000013	Peter, I'm very interested to hear a bit about your early life.
POD1000000014_S0000014	Where were you born and tell us a bit about the values that were instilled in you when you grew up.
POD1000000014_S0000015	Thank you, Rob. I was born in Dublin. I was born into a fairly ordinary working class home.
POD1000000014_S0000016	My dad was a mechanic with the state transport company. My mother was, as was the case with many in the day, a housewife.
POD1000000014_S0000017	We lived a very ordinary family life.
POD1000000014_S0000018	I didn't enjoy school. I was taught by the Christian Brothers, so I have some of my learning to thank them for,
POD1000000014_S0000019	but I wouldn't say they contributed to a very happy school days, but the rest of my childhood was very enjoyable.
POD1000000014_S0000020	My mother would have been quite religious. It was a very different Ireland at the time.
POD1000000014_S0000021	Our house was busy. There were often relatives or neighbours popping in for cups of tea.
POD1000000014_S0000022	And so it was a pleasant place to grow up.
POD1000000014_S0000023	So you had a community service background before going to work in local government, that's correct isn't it?
POD1000000014_S0000024	Yes, I worked for the Welsh Housing Agency when it was set up that was funding housing associations on special needs housing.
POD1000000014_S0000025	But then I went to work for Cardiff Housing Department.
POD1000000014_S0000026	I was responsible for services like homelessness, sheltered housing for older people and so on.
POD1000000014_S0000027	and also managed the Gypsy sites in Cardiff. So a very interesting job.
POD1000000014_S0000028	but I gradually became more involved in mainstream housing through that.
POD1000000014_S0000029	And then before you became Welsh Ombudsman, you were Chief Executive of the Arts Council of Wales. Was that good fun?
POD1000000014_S0000030	It was very good fun. It was at a time shortly after the creation of the Welsh Assembly
POD1000000014_S0000031	The government in Wales was interested in nation building, if you like, doing things to bring people together, and they saw the arts as a valuable way of doing that.
POD1000000014_S0000032	From my perspective, obviously, I was also interested in community arts and arts outreach to people who were otherwise excluded.
POD1000000014_S0000033	So it fitted very well for me. I've never had any expertise in the arts, but I greatly enjoyed it.
POD1000000014_S0000034	And it was a very good time for the arts in Wales.
POD1000000014_S0000035	Now, I think you must be one of the very few people to have occupied national ombudsman jobs in more than one country.
POD1000000014_S0000036	I don't know whether there's anyone else like you in that regard. But what was it like moving from being ombudsman in Wales to ombudsman in Ireland?
POD1000000014_S0000037	It was interesting.
POD1000000014_S0000038	I think the Ombudsman in Wales was a very significant player in the evolution of the devolved administration in Wales.
POD1000000014_S0000039	but particularly the work focused within the health sphere.
POD1000000014_S0000040	And an awful lot of the complaints that we dealt with were to do with clinical judgments.
POD1000000014_S0000041	So moving to Ireland, firstly, I found that I don't have jurisdiction over clinical judgment.
POD1000000014_S0000042	But also I have jurisdiction over a much broader range of government services and local government.
POD1000000014_S0000043	So it was similar in some ways to Wales, but it was a bigger job, if you like.
POD1000000014_S0000044	in the context of a whole national government and a different set of issues to deal with.
POD1000000014_S0000045	In Ireland you're also, you wear many hats, you're also the information commissioner
POD1000000014_S0000046	and you deal with local government standards as well.
POD1000000014_S0000047	Do you find that an advantage in terms of being ombudsman?
POD1000000014_S0000048	It's very helpful if you're committed to the same kinds of principles. You're committed to good public services, you're committed to openness, you're committed to transparency.
POD1000000014_S0000049	Those values work across all of the different hats I wear.
POD1000000014_S0000050	I suppose the biggest difference is as Ombudsman you make recommendations, but in Ireland, in the history of the office, they've always been implemented.
POD1000000014_S0000051	As information commissioner, you make binding decisions, but those get challenged in the courts.
POD1000000014_S0000052	So despite what many people think to be the case, being an ombudsman in some ways is more effective in terms of having outcomes achieved than having binding powers as information commissioners.
POD1000000014_S0000053	What would you say have been the biggest challenges to you as Irish ombudsman?
POD1000000014_S0000054	You've obviously successfully dealt with them because you've been reappointed for a second term. But looking back on the six years that you've had, what are the biggest challenges?
POD1000000014_S0000055	The biggest challenge we faced was with the investigation into the Magdalene laundries.
POD1000000014_S0000056	As we looked more closely at the issues there, this was about women who had been held against their will
POD1000000014_S0000057	Often young women who'd had babies, sometimes school children, had been held against their will and forced to work for many years in laundries.
POD1000000014_S0000058	What I was looking at was a government compensation scheme, and the Department of Justice had chosen to interpret that scheme very narrowly.
POD1000000014_S0000059	So they were excluding young women, people who at the time were young women and had worked in the laundries, but being detained in industrial schools, which
POD1000000014_S0000060	which shared the same sites as the laundries, but not technically resident in the laundries.
POD1000000014_S0000061	So we looked at that and felt that there was a huge injustice, but the initial response of the department was to reject our findings.
POD1000000014_S0000062	So that required a high publicity campaign, which ultimately led to the government changing its mind
POD1000000014_S0000063	To be fair, I suspect if ministers had been involved from the outset, I don't think that the rejection we initially saw would have happened.
POD1000000014_S0000064	Did any of the people who experienced this detriment get in touch with you, or was this a nature of you seeing the unfairness and acting on their behalf?
POD1000000014_S0000065	No, we had a small number of cases, but we investigated the whole scheme. So some of the people who benefited wouldn't even have known of my office.
POD1000000014_S0000066	So that's the advantage of having the power of own initiative to an ombudsman.
POD1000000014_S0000067	Yes, it is. You can investigate
POD1000000014_S0000068	Even if you get complaints, sometimes you're constrained because you can only investigate on the facts if you can't undertake own initiative investigations.
POD1000000014_S0000069	If something comes up that needs to be looked at, there's no constraints on me looking at that.
POD1000000014_S0000070	And particularly, I've found that in the context of excluded groups, it's a very powerful tool to use to make sure that people who don't come to you can nonetheless have access to justice.
POD1000000014_S0000071	Yeah, and is that regarded as controversial in Ireland? I wouldn't have thought so.
POD1000000014_S0000072	No, no, it's just part of the toolkit available to the office. I don't think anybody gives it any second thought.
POD1000000014_S0000073	Now, you behaved very bravely in this investigation because at one point when you were being blocked by ministers, you threatened to go to the
POD1000000014_S0000075	Is that right?
POD1000000014_S0000076	When I was being blocked by officials, I went to the Minister for Justice and threw him to the
POD1000000014_S0000078	the prime minister.
POD1000000014_S0000079	I asked that they personally look to resolve the matter because it was such a stark injustice and reflected very poorly on the government of Ireland.
POD1000000014_S0000081	and the Minister for Justice both acted with great expediency and the matter was resolved almost immediately following their intervention.
POD1000000014_S0000082	I don't think you can be an effective ombudsman without having the kind of guts that you've shown throughout this.
POD1000000014_S0000083	And I hope you will sympathise with those Ombudsman that don't have own initiative powers because it seems to me to be a great handicap.
POD1000000014_S0000084	I think it is. I mean, even in a Welsh context where I didn't have them at the time,
POD1000000014_S0000085	You could be investigating something in one health board and see immediately that it was likely that the same problems were arising elsewhere.
POD1000000014_S0000086	But technically, you couldn't extend your investigation beyond the body you were investigating.
POD1000000014_S0000087	That ability to extend an investigation to cover whichever bodies are involved is very powerful.
POD1000000014_S0000088	So a lot of my work, let's say, with asylum seekers and refugees in accommodation provided on behalf of the government,
POD1000000014_S0000089	I will be looking at complaints that are to do with healthcare, that are to do with access to benefits, that are to do with all kinds of things, access to housing,
POD1000000014_S0000090	other than the services provided by the Department of Justice in providing the accommodation.
POD1000000014_S0000091	So it is just that capacity to broaden out an investigation as well as the capacity to instigate an investigation where you don't have complaints.
POD1000000014_S0000092	Now, my current own initiative investigation is looking at the situation of people under 65 living in nursing homes.
POD1000000014_S0000093	That's become a much more pressing issue in the coronavirus crisis. One of the people we've interviewed has already died. Another has contracted the virus.
POD1000000014_S0000094	So, although at this point it's not possible for obvious reasons to conclude the investigation,
POD1000000014_S0000095	What we have done is written to the leaders of all the political parties who are currently involved in talks leading to the formation of a new government.
POD1000000014_S0000096	to highlight the issue of people in institutional care, so that at least what we've learned to date in the course of our investigation can hopefully help to shape the policies of the incoming government.
POD1000000014_S0000097	Can we just move on a little bit?
POD1000000014_S0000098	You are the president of the International Ombudsman Institute, which is a very important and prestigious job, which is very valuable to ombudsmen all over the world.
POD1000000014_S0000099	What added value do you think the IOI brings to our discussions?
POD1000000014_S0000100	I think one of the very important things is straightforwardly learning from each other.
POD1000000014_S0000101	Being an ombudsman is necessarily an isolated role. What you can't do is be too close to the people in the services which are within your jurisdictions.
POD1000000014_S0000102	So consequently, we have more in common with each other than we do with the people whose services we're looking at and learning from each other is very important.
POD1000000014_S0000103	The IOI provides structured training opportunities. That's been one of the very valuable things we've done.
POD1000000014_S0000104	It provides best practice papers to show how things can best be done.
POD1000000014_S0000105	And of course, Rob, you yourself have been responsible for the best practice paper on peer review and the work you've done in that field.
POD1000000014_S0000106	But also, I think the IOI has played a big part in supporting ombudsman organisations under threat.
POD1000000014_S0000107	We've seen, for instance, colleagues in many countries around the world who, because they're doing their job, are being threatened or ignored by their governments.
POD1000000014_S0000108	And we've seen things like budgets being cut. We've seen people being denounced by government ministers and so on.
POD1000000014_S0000109	So the solidarity of the international ombudsman community is very important, but we also intervene quite directly
POD1000000014_S0000110	I'll give an example of Cyprus, where the Auditor General was looking to interfere in the work of the Ombudsman's office.
POD1000000014_S0000111	following intervention from the IOI and others with the government of Cyprus, the parliament in particular, the threats were withdrawn.
POD1000000014_S0000112	In Poland, the Ombudsman was threatened with large cuts to his budget. We sent in a commission of inquiry.
POD1000000014_S0000113	We interviewed government ministers, we interviewed the judiciary,
POD1000000014_S0000114	We carried out press conferences, we talked to NGOs, and we managed to get a stay of execution
POD1000000014_S0000115	And so we saw major threats to democracy there, but our intervention along with those of others has helped to ensure that that office is still there and is continuing to operate effectively.
POD1000000014_S0000116	that Polish intervention was crucial
POD1000000014_S0000117	And what's one of the remarkable things about it was that you actually went there didn't just talk about it and
POD1000000014_S0000118	but you put the political institutions under pressure by asking them to give an account of what they were doing.
POD1000000014_S0000119	Absolutely so. We did that in person and we did it through the media so that it had a very high profile within Poland. I think it's no good
POD1000000014_S0000120	I did the same in Cyprus, media interviews, talking to people on the ground.
POD1000000014_S0000121	I think it's really important that solidarity is not something that comes just in the form of a letter, though sometimes a letter can be effective enough in itself.
POD1000000014_S0000122	but that you actually scale the intervention to the nature of the challenge.
POD1000000014_S0000123	We've talked about this quite a lot when we've not been on the radio, but
POD1000000014_S0000124	How important do you think it is that we as Ombuds do not get involved in political matters?
POD1000000014_S0000125	Or do you think this is a cultural relic of British imperialism?
POD1000000014_S0000127	Whatever about British imperialism? No, I think it's a very complex question.
POD1000000014_S0000128	I think that for an ombudsman not to be involved in politics is scarcely possible because what we're actually doing is overseeing services provided by the state.
POD1000000014_S0000129	And so therefore, any comment we make on those services has the potential to be political.
POD1000000014_S0000130	What we can't be is party political, and what we can't do is speak beyond the evidence of our casebook.
POD1000000014_S0000131	So I talked earlier on about seeking to affect the formation of the government in Ireland to promote particular policies to favour disadvantaged groups of people.
POD1000000014_S0000132	But I'm doing that on the basis of investigations I'm carrying out
POD1000000014_S0000133	I'm not doing it as Peter Tyndall's citizen. I'm doing it as Ombudsman of Ireland based on the evidence from my case book.
POD1000000014_S0000134	And under those circumstances, I think it's entirely appropriate to intervene.
POD1000000014_S0000135	I think it becomes problematic if people are seen to be intervening on issues which go beyond their own work as ombudsman.
POD1000000014_S0000136	And I think that's where it would become problematic.
POD1000000014_S0000137	But I do think that if you've got evidence, then it's important that you use that evidence where it can be most effective in securing justice for the people who've come to you.
POD1000000014_S0000138	So we're moving towards the end but I wanted to ask you about how you're coping with the coronavirus.
POD1000000014_S0000139	what sort of impact has it had short term and longer term on the way you operate?
POD1000000014_S0000140	Yeah, it's an interesting one.
POD1000000014_S0000141	The first thing was that we surprised ourselves by being able to get ourselves in a position to work remotely much quicker than we might have done otherwise.
POD1000000014_S0000142	I suppose if it's proved anything, it's that when there is a crisis, it's surprising how long-term problems can be solved in a hurry.
POD1000000014_S0000143	And so we've been able to operate all of our services more or less without change throughout the crisis.
POD1000000014_S0000144	We've had some changes in volumes of work coming to us.
POD1000000014_S0000145	we've put a bit more emphasis on project work, but by and large, people are able to make their complaints to us
POD1000000014_S0000146	they can ring us, they can email us,
POD1000000014_S0000147	They can contact us on the web
POD1000000014_S0000148	And we're even able to collect our posts, though we're discouraging people from using the post at the moment. But the effect of that is that we can keep going.
POD1000000014_S0000149	The difficulties we face are probably more to do with the difficulties being faced by the services we're dealing with.
POD1000000014_S0000150	So we've told the health service, we've told nursing homes, and we've told the Department of Social Protection, which deals with benefits and pensions,
POD1000000014_S0000151	that we understand that it will take them longer to respond to us and that in some instances they won't be able to.
POD1000000014_S0000152	So we understand that. But in general, we've been able to keep going.
POD1000000014_S0000153	Just to give an example of the kind of things we've been dealing with
POD1000000014_S0000154	We had one gentleman stuck in Poland who couldn't get back to Ireland, who'd been denied benefit in Ireland, even though his wife and children were in Ireland and he normally lived and worked there.
POD1000000014_S0000155	and we were able to intervene successfully so that he got his benefits. So we're able to deal with issues as they arise.
POD1000000014_S0000156	I think in the longer term, there'll be two things, really. One of them is just practical.
POD1000000014_S0000157	We now know that it's possible for more of our people to work effectively from home. And I can't see us going back to the situation before where only a very small number of people did that.
POD1000000014_S0000158	I think more people will work from home as a consequence of what we've learned during the crisis.
POD1000000014_S0000159	But the second issue for me has been the appalling death toll among people in institutional care, many of whom shouldn't be there.
POD1000000014_S0000160	And I think we have to redouble our efforts in working on their behalf after the crisis to make sure that should there be a resurgence or should something else like this come along,
POD1000000014_S0000161	that they're not as exposed and as vulnerable as they are at the moment.
POD1000000014_S0000162	It makes complete sense for the Ombudsman to be looking at both health and social care matters.
POD1000000014_S0000163	and not, as in this country, to have a separation where one ombudsman looks at social care and the other looks at health.
POD1000000014_S0000164	If I may, Rob, just add something.
POD1000000014_S0000165	One of the things that's noticeably different between Ireland and the UK, and England in particular, is that there is a single national ombudsman in Ireland.
POD1000000014_S0000166	so that issues of health and social care both come into my jurisdiction.
POD1000000014_S0000167	The reality is these are complex interlinked issues.
POD1000000014_S0000168	and trying to deal with them with two separate ombudsmen in the office is as complicated enough as it is
POD1000000014_S0000169	Trying to do so in the context where you have MP filters
POD1000000014_S0000170	where you have different systems applying in different parts of the UK, it's impossibly difficult for yourselves
POD1000000014_S0000171	but you manage it very well along with the local government ombudsman.
POD1000000014_S0000172	I have to say you've managed in practice to overcome the difficulties, but it's also an impossibly complex scenario for complainants
POD1000000014_S0000173	In Ireland, somebody wants to complain about public services, they come to my office.
POD1000000014_S0000174	In your case, it's much more complicated.
POD1000000014_S0000175	And I do hope that the proposals for ombudsman reform that we've seen in the UK over recent years are not entirely lost.
POD1000000014_S0000176	and that we do come to a much more satisfactory situation where there's a proper national ombudsman and where people can bring their complaints, regardless of what particular public service they are complaining about.
POD1000000014_S0000177	And I do hope that happens before I die, which I'm increasingly becoming doubtful about, but we'll have to wait and see.
POD1000000014_S0000178	Peter, you conducted the peer review of my organisation and then you appeared before the Select Committee in Parliament.
POD1000000014_S0000179	So that was not an expected development.
POD1000000014_S0000180	What was it like being the peer reviewer who had to go before the UK Parliament?
POD1000000014_S0000181	It was an interesting experience, Rob.
POD1000000014_S0000182	I think it would have been much more challenging if I hadn't been quite so impressed by the quality of the service your office provides.
POD1000000014_S0000183	It wasn't as though when we looked at the service, we used a lot of objective criteria.
POD1000000014_S0000184	And obviously, with any office, there is room for improvement. But in general, I was able to give reassurance to the committee as the quality of service that complainants were receiving
POD1000000014_S0000185	but also to highlight some of the deficiencies in powers and in jurisdiction that are causing you difficulties in practice,
POD1000000014_S0000186	But I suppose what I'd want to say, I was very impressed by the quality of the people in your office.
POD1000000014_S0000187	It was a very good experience. They're very open with us.
POD1000000014_S0000188	We talked to your staff without talking to yourself and the managers. So we were able for people to express a view as they saw fit. And I think people were very complimentary.
POD1000000014_S0000189	So I think, as I say, it was an interesting experience
POD1000000014_S0000190	it's always challenging to go before parliamentary committees. The session was quite searching.
POD1000000014_S0000191	I think the committee wanted to reassure itself that this wasn't some kind of hagiography.
POD1000000014_S0000192	But we were satisfied in the end that we were able to say, no, we've looked in detail at this office.
POD1000000014_S0000193	There are areas which can improve, but by and large, this is an improving service that's delivering good quality ombudsman service to the people of England and to the UK.
POD1000000014_S0000194	Well, I think the structural point is that thanks to the IOI, this whole system of peer review looks like it has legs for the wider ombudsman community.
POD1000000014_S0000195	and it is an effective and inexpensive way of adding to scrutiny of ombudsman schemes. So thank you for the role that you played in pioneering that.
POD1000000014_S0000196	One thing beyond that too, Rob, is that
POD1000000014_S0000197	Since the review was undertaken, the IOI, along with other bodies, have worked quite hard
POD1000000014_S0000198	with the Venice Commission and the Council of Europe in developing a set of overriding principles for ombudsman offices, the Venice principles as they've become known.
POD1000000014_S0000199	and they've now been adopted by the Council of Europe.
POD1000000014_S0000200	And that's the first time there's been a proper international standard against which ombuds offices can be judged.
POD1000000014_S0000201	And so I'm keen to see them being used as they are being used now in the context of peer reviews.
POD1000000014_S0000202	so that there is an objective set of internationally recognized standards against which you're measuring a particular ombudsman office.
POD1000000014_S0000203	So I think that's, again, marks another step forward and one that I'm very pleased to have seen develop.
POD1000000014_S0000204	I think when I undertook the peer review of the Catalonian Ombudsman with my Belgian counterpart,
POD1000000014_S0000205	we used those very same Venice Principles as a benchmark against which to judge the Catalonian Ombudsman.
POD1000000014_S0000206	And it is very helpful to have that because it's without prejudice.
POD1000000014_S0000207	It applies to everyone. So I think it is an important development.
POD1000000014_S0000208	So two final questions. How have you, Peter Tindall, reacted to working remotely, being at home with your family?
POD1000000014_S0000209	I've enjoyed it, to be honest.
POD1000000014_S0000210	It hasn't been too frustrating. The technology can be an issue from time to time, but it hasn't been too difficult
POD1000000014_S0000211	It's been less difficult than I would have expected.
POD1000000014_S0000212	And as time goes on, I think the issue of visible leadership comes into it, doesn't
POD1000000014_S0000213	So, you know, you actually want to be with your people again. But it's worked surprisingly well.
POD1000000014_S0000214	And...
POD1000000014_S0000215	As I say, I think for the office itself, I think we'll see more remote working in the future.
POD1000000014_S0000216	Thank you. So lastly then, what I always ask my guests,
POD1000000014_S0000217	What advice would you give to young colleagues newly arriving as caseworkers in the embryonic ombudsman profession?
POD1000000014_S0000218	For me, there's a couple of characteristics that have to be embodied by people working in the service or as an ombudsman.
POD1000000014_S0000219	We have to be objective. We have to be fair.
POD1000000014_S0000220	We have to be even handed. So the first advice often is make sure you know the whole story before you reach a conclusion.
POD1000000014_S0000221	But underpinning all of that, I would say that if you haven't got a passionate commitment to justice, then you're in the wrong job.
POD1000000014_S0000222	Because what this fundamentally is about is people who believe in fairness, people who believe in justice, and people who want to use their own efforts to make sure that nobody is denied access to justice.
POD1000000014_S0000223	And that's what we're here for.
POD1000000014_S0000224	Thank you so much, Peter.
POD1000000014_S0000225	your answers were stimulating and also inspirational
POD1000000014_S0000227	We're all very grateful for the time you've given for this interview.
POD1000000014_S0000228	Thanks a lot.
POD1000000014_S0000230	My next guest will be the Catalonian Ombudsman, Rafael Ribó.
POD1000000014_S0000231	So he'll be joining us from Barcelona.
POD1000000014_S0000232	In the meantime, this is Rob Behrens on behalf of Radio Ombudsman and saying have a good day and stay safe.
POD1000000017_S0000001	From the New York Times Magazine, I'm Nicole Hannah-Jones. This is 1619.
POD1000000017_S0000003	This week, Wesley Morris on the birth of American music.
POD1000000017_S0000005	So last fall, I am at my friend's house. We are making dinner. I'm chopping vegetables. And I asked my friend Brett, who was cooking with me, can you put on some music?
POD1000000017_S0000006	And he said, what do you want to listen to? And I said, have you ever heard of Yacht Rock? And he said, what? I said, Yacht Rock, have you ever heard of this? And he goes, no, I have not.
POD1000000017_S0000007	So he finds the yacht rock station in Pandora, which I don't know why or how he's still a Pandora guy with all due respect to Pandora. He is one. And he finds the Iraq station.
POD1000000017_S0000009	At some point, Bright has to go run an errand. I think I might have sent him on one. I don't remember. But he's gone, so I'm alone. Just me with the vegetables and Yodrock.
POD1000000017_S0000011	It gives me plenty of time to really think about the songs I'm hearing.
POD1000000017_S0000013	We're talking about music made between the years of, I don't know, I would say like 1975 to about 1983. Things like...
POD1000000017_S0000015	Aces how long?
POD1000000017_S0000017	Seals and Croft doing Summer Breeze. I'm hearing things like
POD1000000017_S0000019	Steal Away by Robby Dupree.
POD1000000017_S0000021	And the Doobie Brothers, what a fool believes.
POD1000000017_S0000023	It is like our soft, raucous period in American popular music.
POD1000000017_S0000025	The joke of Yacht Rock is that whoever invented it, whoever's making a playlist out of these songs is basically saying that they're inconsequential and that what's in them doesn't matter.
POD1000000017_S0000027	But what I know I'm hearing is something bigger and deeper than that.
POD1000000017_S0000029	Every song has something about it that is similar to the other songs.
POD1000000017_S0000031	I'm hearing things like Rosanna by Toto.
POD1000000017_S0000033	which seems perfectly banal, has a really good beat. It sort of builds to its chorus.
POD1000000017_S0000035	But then at the end,
POD1000000017_S0000037	I'm hearing
POD1000000017_S0000039	The great doo-wop harmonies of the 50s and 60s.
POD1000000017_S0000041	There is something jazz-like in the syncopated music of something like Steely Dan.
POD1000000017_S0000043	You can hear in somebody like Michael McDonald.
POD1000000017_S0000045	That is like a gospel breakdown.
POD1000000017_S0000047	What I am hearing in all of these songs is basically blackness.
POD1000000017_S0000049	And the song in which I am hearing it the deepest and strongest and most powerfully, at least to me, standing in that kitchen, chopping those vegetables, was when Kenny Loggins' This Is It comes on.
POD1000000017_S0000051	It's got a kind of loosely disco-like rhythm to it. There's a lot of percussion sort of going back and forth and around.
POD1000000017_S0000053	Kenny Loggins is basically sing whispering the verses of this song.
POD1000000017_S0000055	doing this very light
POD1000000017_S0000056	cool
POD1000000017_S0000058	And then in the pre-chorus, Kenny Loggins disappears and who shows up? Michael McDonald.
POD1000000017_S0000060	Giving Kenny Loggins plenty of time to gather himself.
POD1000000017_S0000062	When he sings the word miracle, he doesn't sing miracle. He goes, miracle.
POD1000000017_S0000064	Like he is scraping the bottom of a pan to get all of the good bits off of it before you pour the gravy in.
POD1000000017_S0000066	Scraping the pan is the blackest thing you can do as a singer. And here's Kenny Loggins as this white artist doing it.
POD1000000017_S0000068	And then the gravy comes.
POD1000000017_S0000070	He is like at the top of the church at this point.
POD1000000017_S0000071	He has like elevated himself to the rafters. There's like no more. He is like at the roof trying to clear a way to get to heaven. But there's just church roof in the way.
POD1000000017_S0000073	He's not the greatest singer, but there's a kind of gumption and nerve to the singing of this song.
POD1000000017_S0000075	that cannot be denied. A tip of the hat to him.
POD1000000017_S0000076	I just had to stand there and I just, I actually cracked up. I just put down the knife and I cracked up. And it felt so pleasurable. And then I started thinking about all these other singers I love.
POD1000000017_S0000078	I'm thinking about Amy Winehouse.
POD1000000017_S0000080	I'm thinking about Annie Lennox.
POD1000000017_S0000082	Think about George Michael.
POD1000000017_S0000084	I think about Chris Stapleton.
POD1000000017_S0000085	who practices a kind of muscly blues that gets written off his country because he's a big white guy in a hat.
POD1000000017_S0000087	And one of the many phases in which David Bowie really wanted to make R&B and soul music.
POD1000000017_S0000089	This is the sound not just of Black America, but the sound of America. It is deeply American, almost especially when it's sung by British people like David Bowie and Annie Lennox and Amy Winehouse.
POD1000000017_S0000090	And it fills me with pride. Like, I know that there is something irresistible and ultimately inevitable about Black music being a part of American popular music.
POD1000000017_S0000091	But it also reminds me that there's a history to this, a very painful history. And in the most perversely ironic way, it's this historical pain that is responsible for this music.
POD1000000017_S0000093	Some of the oldest recordings we have of Black American music are from the 1930s.
POD1000000017_S0000094	And they're songs that would have been sung by Americans born into slavery. There's this one called Old Ship of Zion.
POD1000000017_S0000095	You can hear in it these four men. Their voices are moving in and out of each other.
POD1000000017_S0000097	And it's beautiful. And it's also sad. You can feel that in your bones.
POD1000000017_S0000098	And then there would be music that was completely the opposite, like old Coon Dog, for instance.
POD1000000017_S0000100	You can hear the playfulness in the song.
POD1000000017_S0000102	And you've got this banjo, this great African instrument that becomes the bedrock of American music in so many ways. And that thing is dancing.
POD1000000017_S0000103	And then you have someone like Billy McRae.
POD1000000017_S0000104	And, oh my God, you can hear in his singing what we would now call something like the live long day.
POD1000000017_S0000106	Years and years of hard work.
POD1000000017_S0000107	and unimaginable sorrow.
POD1000000017_S0000109	You can also hear in all of this music,
POD1000000017_S0000111	this undeniable sound of hope.
POD1000000017_S0000113	All of these melodies and cadences and emotions are things that would have been passed down generation after generation. It's what you would have heard on a plantation. It's what you would have heard walking by a plantation.
POD1000000017_S0000114	It's what you would have heard passing a black person doing his job, entertaining himself doing the drudgery of work, the way a guy named Thomas Dartmouth Rice did sometime around the 1830s.
POD1000000017_S0000115	As the story goes, T.D. Rice, a white man, this anonymous nobody actor trying to make ends meet,
POD1000000017_S0000116	One day he's touring with a troop in Cincinnati, or maybe it was Pittsburgh. We don't really know. But the myth basically goes, T.D. Race happened upon an old black man cleaning a horse in a stable.
POD1000000017_S0000117	The man was doing his job on property owned by a white man named Crow.
POD1000000017_S0000119	He heard the tune this old black man was singing. He saw the way this man moved his body as he was cleaning this horse.
POD1000000017_S0000120	Now, we don't know what tune this old man would have been singing.
POD1000000017_S0000122	Whatever Reiss hears coming out of this man's mouth is captivating to him. And what he sees is an opportunity.
POD1000000017_S0000124	Because showbiz in the 1830s looked like this.
POD1000000017_S0000126	Italian operas,
POD1000000017_S0000128	British plays, entertainment, imported from Europe. All the people performing this stuff would have been white, the audiences would have been white,
POD1000000017_S0000129	After all, it's 1830. Slavery is in full effect.
POD1000000017_S0000131	And when it came to entertainment, there was nothing new, nothing truly American.
POD1000000017_S0000133	And so when T.D. Rice hears this Black man singing this song and moving his body in this particular way, ding, a light bulb goes off.
POD1000000017_S0000134	And he takes that light bulb and runs all the way to the theater. He figures out a way to melt down some cork.
POD1000000017_S0000135	Let's it cool, presumably takes a rag or maybe even his hand if it's cool enough.
POD1000000017_S0000137	And then he paints his face black.
POD1000000017_S0000139	He goes out on stage, but instead of doing his regular act, he's got this horse groomers tune, except now he's given the tune lyrics.
POD1000000017_S0000140	Come listen, all you gals and boys. I'm just from Tuckahoe. I'm going to sing a little song. My name's Jim Crow.
POD1000000017_S0000142	And the lyrics give the horse groomer a name. And the name is Jim Crow.
POD1000000017_S0000144	So the crowd goes crazy. They go so bananas, the man gets 20 encores.
POD1000000017_S0000146	This is the first time a paying audience is basically electrified by a white man with a black face. This is the night that Jim Crow was allegedly introduced to America, this mascot of American racism.
POD1000000017_S0000147	And this is what America really wanted, which was its own original art form that is not an Italian opera. It isn't some British guy coming over and that's being all over them.
POD1000000017_S0000148	And here is Thomas Dartmouth Rice giving it to them. This is the night that American popular culture was born.
POD1000000017_S0000150	Oh boy. I mean, you know how it goes. This sensational thing happens, and then everybody wants to get on the bandwagon and do their own.
POD1000000017_S0000151	So you have other minstrel acts who come along and try to do what Thomas Dartmouth Rice is doing, a song and a dance.
POD1000000017_S0000152	and a black face on their white skin.
POD1000000017_S0000154	And then from these solo acts, you have basically bands forming.
POD1000000017_S0000156	And the bands have all the instruments that you would have in a band that you'd recognize now. There's a banjo and a fiddle and some tambourines and percussion in the form of bones, which would come from a pig sometimes.
POD1000000017_S0000157	That is the formation of what will become the minstrel troupe.
POD1000000017_S0000159	And the place that minstrelsy took hold was in the North.
POD1000000017_S0000160	places like Philadelphia and New York and Boston, where you'd have these theaters dedicated to minstrel acts, where minstrel acts would just move into a theater and do their act night after night after night after night after night.
POD1000000017_S0000161	And a lot of these performers have never been meaningfully South to have a meaningful relationship with Black people. And so they just made stuff up based on what they thought Black people were like.
POD1000000017_S0000163	They were able to draw on things that were coming to America from other parts of Europe, like the polka.
POD1000000017_S0000165	And so you had, over the course of the formation of this culture, an inherent mixing. You had some amazing mix of... ...an imagined Blackness
POD1000000017_S0000166	Real, actual Irish melodies and Polish music with what we would now call gospel, but spiritual harmonies interlaced together with this African banjo.
POD1000000017_S0000168	Basically welding into a fusion that becomes the thing that everybody wants to try to do.
POD1000000017_S0000170	The whole thing just sweeps the nation and for the rest of the 19th century, this is the shit. Can we say that?
POD1000000017_S0000172	And so for the rest of the 19th century, this is the shit.
POD1000000017_S0000174	This is America's primary form of entertainment. People are going crazy for black-faced minstrels. You have little boys going to bed and dreaming about how they can become part of this minstrel show.
POD1000000017_S0000175	Some of those people having these dreams go on to become people like Stephen Foster.
POD1000000017_S0000177	Stephen Foster, the man widely credited as being the father of American music.
POD1000000017_S0000179	Some of his songs, some of his most famous songs, songs you know, songs you love, songs you still sing, songs your children, if you have them, they still sing. Some of those songs were written for blackface performers.
POD1000000017_S0000181	And if you listen to something like Camp Town Races, you can hear in it all of its minstrel properties.
POD1000000017_S0000183	The song, of course, is written in so-called Negro dialect. I mean, instead of saying, go in, you're saying, gwine.
POD1000000017_S0000185	Like instead of saying O-F for of, you get a lot of D-E for duh.
POD1000000017_S0000187	This is a white person imagining how a black person would sing this song.
POD1000000017_S0000188	And that was a Gold Rush era hit.
POD1000000017_S0000190	This is the I want to hold your hand of 1851.
POD1000000017_S0000192	Part of the problem that we still live with now is that it was so much the heart and soul of American culture that it wasn't that it became not racist.
POD1000000017_S0000193	It just was a thing that you did. If you wanted to be an entertainer at any point after 1830, you in all likelihood were at least going to try to be a blackface minstrel, even if you were black.
POD1000000017_S0000195	After the Civil War ends and there's an opportunity for Black people to perform, they have to do what the nation wants. And what the nation wants at that point is Blackface.
POD1000000017_S0000196	And now, giving you Noise in Tempo.
POD1000000017_S0000197	F.B. Miller and Scatman Corolla.
POD1000000017_S0000198	So black people blacked up and performed as black people who weren't actually black.
POD1000000017_S0000200	By the time you have black people painting their faces black to perform as black people, the only question you can really ask at this point is what the hell is going on? Why is this happening?
POD1000000017_S0000201	What was so captivating about seeing Black people represented this way? Why would a white audience have clamored for it so much? I think one of the things that it offered was an opportunity to feel good about a thing that actually felt really bad at the time.
POD1000000017_S0000202	people were really torn about whether to continue with slavery or whether to abolish it. The Minstrel Show didn't really give you an answer,
POD1000000017_S0000203	but it provided a platform by which you could either escape from actually having to think about that question that really was tearing the nation apart, or depending on which show you would wind up seeing,
POD1000000017_S0000204	It fully engaged you in the lightest possible way about enslaved people and how you didn't really have to feel so bad for them because they like being enslaved. You got to laugh at a thing that you actually felt so anguished about.
POD1000000017_S0000205	you get to watch these Black people who are really a source of national agony outside the theater become fools inside the theater. And in sitting in that theater, watching these white men in blackface make fools of Black people
POD1000000017_S0000206	A white audience could feel cultured. They could feel civilized. They could feel superior to the people they were watching be made fun of.
POD1000000017_S0000207	And in a crazy way, watching them dehumanize what really have been an opportunity for a white audience to feel so much better about their own humanity.
POD1000000017_S0000209	By the time you get to the 20th century, minstrelsy is still with us. It is the basis upon which American movies are built. This country's first movie blockbuster.
POD1000000017_S0000210	D.W. Griffith's The Birth of a Nation, full of white men, villainously in blackface.
POD1000000017_S0000212	And America's first talking motion picture.
POD1000000017_S0000214	The Jazz Singer. About a Jewish man who feels most himself not as a Jewish man struggling with his Jewish identity and pleasing his cantor father. No, no!
POD1000000017_S0000216	It's when he blacks his face up and performs Mammy as a Negro.
POD1000000017_S0000218	Some of America's favorite stars did numbers in blackface.
POD1000000017_S0000220	Judy Garland performed in blackface.
POD1000000017_S0000222	Bing Crosby and Fred Astaire both performed in blackface.
POD1000000017_S0000224	White Christmas has a whole number. The most famous number in White Christmas involves a blackface tune.
POD1000000017_S0000226	But at the same time, there's the beginnings of a recording industry. And you had Black artists who had access to recording studios.
POD1000000017_S0000227	Out of these recordings, you have people like Muddy Waters.
POD1000000017_S0000229	inventing and perfecting blues rhythm, blues ideas, blues expression, the expression of
POD1000000017_S0000231	of a fully human black self in American popular art.
POD1000000017_S0000233	He had a kind of confidence that most people would never have heard coming from a Black person before.
POD1000000017_S0000235	And this is just the beginning.
POD1000000017_S0000237	You have the advent of a place like Blue Note Records where lots of amazing jazz was created and then released into the world. People like Sidney Bechet.
POD1000000017_S0000239	Ruby Armstrong.
POD1000000017_S0000241	and Duke Ellington.
POD1000000017_S0000243	You have Black musicians thinking about how to move not only music forward, but American culture forward.
POD1000000017_S0000245	Thinking about how these instruments can do other things besides make what we think of as Western European classical music.
POD1000000017_S0000247	Taking music to a place that nobody had ever tried to previously take it.
POD1000000017_S0000249	people who just kept pushing it forward and beyond.
POD1000000017_S0000251	And then you have the development of the single most important movement black people have ever had artistically.
POD1000000017_S0000253	And that is the advent of Motown Records.
POD1000000017_S0000255	Motown is the most powerful mass-produced expression of Black glamour, of Black self-confidence, of Black self-reliance.
POD1000000017_S0000257	Its project was to get black producers, black musicians, black singers to take quote white, quote Western musical ideas of orchestration, strings and horns,
POD1000000017_S0000259	in straightforward harmonies
POD1000000017_S0000261	and you marry them to a Black Weekend.
POD1000000017_S0000263	Where on Saturday night you're at a juke joint, having a good time with rhythm and blues music, guitar and drum and bass.
POD1000000017_S0000265	Sex, basically.
POD1000000017_S0000267	And then you go home slightly hungover.
POD1000000017_S0000269	And you wake up and you go to church on Sunday morning.
POD1000000017_S0000271	where there's a whole other musical experience involving hand claps and different harmonic arrangements and call and response.
POD1000000017_S0000273	A lot of feeling, a lot of oomph, a lot of gratitude.
POD1000000017_S0000275	You have the combination of these three different areas of musical expression happening at the same time in just about every single Motown record.
POD1000000017_S0000277	And whether it's the four tops doing reach out, I'll be there.
POD1000000017_S0000279	or Martha and the Vendellas doing heatwave.
POD1000000017_S0000281	On something like Heat Wave, you can hear hands slapping the tambourine like it actually is Sunday morning.
POD1000000017_S0000283	then when everything is firing,
POD1000000017_S0000285	It's just the most exciting, romantic sound you're ever going to hear. And at the center of it is what can only be described as a refulgent, tasteful blackness.
POD1000000017_S0000287	Here you have in Motown a force that is actively combating these ideas of Black people as being inherently inferior.
POD1000000017_S0000289	Motown is the antidote to American minstrelsy.
POD1000000017_S0000291	And this is what I was thinking about standing there in that kitchen, chopping those vegetables. It's the thing that made me laugh was just how all that history is
POD1000000017_S0000292	is just very silently coursing through this music. It might not even be aware that it's even there. It's so thoroughly atomized into American culture. It's going to show up in ways that even people making the art can't quite put their finger on.
POD1000000017_S0000294	What you're hearing in Black music that's so appealing to so many people of all races across time is possibility, struggle, it is strife, it is humor,
POD1000000017_S0000295	It is sex. It is confidence. And that's ironic, because this is the sound of a people who for decades and centuries have been denied freedom,
POD1000000017_S0000296	And yet, what you respond to in black music is the ultimate expression of a belief in that freedom. The belief that the struggle is worth it, that the pain begets joy,
POD1000000017_S0000297	And that that joy you're experiencing is not only contagious, it's necessary and urgent and irresistible. Black music is American music.
POD1000000017_S0000298	Because as Americans, we say we believe in freedom. And that's what we tell the world. And the power of Black music is that it's the ultimate expression of that belief in American freedom.
POD1000000018_S0000000	When Andy Griffith passed away in 2012, CNN covered his death off and on the entire day.
POD1000000018_S0000001	You've all seen this type of news coverage before. An overview of the career, images of the star in their prime, phone-in conversations with other celebrities who were close with the departed.
POD1000000018_S0000003	Larry King is one of the people who called in to talk that day. He'd had Andy on his various shows numerous times, and he mentioned something in passing that's really interesting.
POD1000000018_S0000005	What Larry said is that a lawyer named Percy Foreman was the man who inspired the character Matlock.
POD1000000018_S0000007	This was a weird thing for anyone to say because most people, even today, believe that character to be based on a different lawyer named Bobby Lee Cook.
POD1000000018_S0000009	However, in 2015, three years after Larry King said something that most people would assume was incorrect, the creator of Matlock did confirm that the character was based on Percy Foreman.
POD1000000018_S0000010	a criminal defense attorney from Houston, Texas, who lost only 53 of the 1,500 cases where clients of his faced the death penalty, with only one of those losses resulting in an actual execution.
POD1000000018_S0000012	Percy was able to achieve this record by being an incredible lawyer, no denying it, but also due to the Texas court system's practice of using juries to determine guilt as well as sentencing in the case of a guilty verdict.
POD1000000018_S0000014	So instead of one judge, who's heard it all before, determining his client's fate,
POD1000000018_S0000016	Percy had 12 average citizens from the local community sitting right there, waiting to be convinced that the victim in this situation wasn't a victim at all.
POD1000000018_S0000017	They were up to no good. The community was far better off without that element in it. And even if his client had killed him, well hell, they needed killing.
POD1000000018_S0000019	Foreman called it misdemeanor murder. That's where a jury might convict you of ending another person's life and send you on your way with the type of punishment you'd receive for a misdemeanor crime.
POD1000000018_S0000020	Often, nothing more than probation. No time at all. It's essentially a sanctioned form of vigilante justice.
POD1000000018_S0000021	Percy Foreman had such a long run of wins with this strategy that it's still being used in Texas today. People who have conversations about this sort of thing will sometimes refer to it as the Texas defense.
POD1000000018_S0000023	Now, Jim Denny wasn't from Texas. He was from Tennessee.
