POD1000000047_S0000101	Can you tell us a bit more about NICE and how they prioritize health treatments within the United Kingdom?
POD1000000047_S0000102	Yeah, I mean, that's something I've worked on as a medical statistician. I've been a huge supporter of NICE. And essentially, what they do is when they decide whether to have a new vaccine or whether to decide to have a new recommend vaccine.
POD1000000047_S0000103	for drugs to be paid for under the NHS, for example, they will look at what is the expected benefit of that intervention and what's the expected cost. And then they look at how much it's going to cost to
POD1000000047_S0000104	and provide an extra what they call a quality adjusted life year. So one year of life that's discounted. If it's poor quality, you will discount it won't be worth the whole year. And then essentially they can make the comparison
POD1000000047_S0000105	And they look if something comes in at less than twenty thousand pounds a quality just almost as paid for, you know, just yet. I will pay for it under the NHS if it's more than about thirty thousand, then they really try to.
POD1000000047_S0000107	We don't want to pay for this.
POD1000000047_S0000108	and try to go back to the drug company to renegotiate a price, for example, between 20,000 and 30,000. Well, you know, that's more in the grey zone. So, and this has been enormously beneficial, partly
POD1000000047_S0000109	in order to go back to drug companies and get them to reduce their prices. But and also to see that some interventions, for example, cancer screening, come in extremely cheap. They're just worth doing. It also means you have to be explicit, for example, on how much you value the future.
POD1000000047_S0000110	rather than the present, because they put in a discount rate, currently 3.5%. Now that means that a year of life in 25 years' time, for example, is only worth about half what a year of life now is worth, and that's taken into account.
POD1000000047_S0000111	And now that, of course, is controversial. And if we are talking about big policy decisions, for example, about climate change, that's far too big a discount rate. We wouldn't care less about the world in 100 years time if we use that discount. So in different areas,
POD1000000047_S0000112	you might be wanting to use a different discount rate. But these are taking economic ideas and moving them into very human decisions
POD1000000047_S0000113	And I think they are enormously helpful and illuminating. But they're never perfect.
POD1000000047_S0000115	Yeah, I've actually written an article with Professor Toby Ord about why we shouldn't discount health, even though we should discount financial returns, about why it's appropriate in one case and not in the other. So we'll put up a link to that on the website.
POD1000000047_S0000116	A lot of people who are planning out their careers, they feel just overwhelmed by uncertainty. They don't know how much they're going to earn in one career or what's the chances of getting into academia or being elected to parliament.
POD1000000047_S0000117	How do you think people ought to make decisions when they're just surrounded by so much uncertainty?
POD1000000047_S0000118	Well, I mean, you could say that we're always surrounded by this. Again, this is common to everything we do. We never know what's going to happen in the future, which is great. People don't want to know what's going to happen in the future. People don't even know what they're going to get for Christmas, let alone what's going to happen for the rest of their lives.
POD1000000047_S0000119	And so this is just a common problem. And we need to distinguish what we might call risk and uncertainty. Risk is when it's a very well-defined problem, the short-term issues, buying lottery tickets when we know what the chances are.
POD1000000047_S0000120	And then we can sort of take a rational approach when we're dealing with deeper uncertainty, when really I'm not even sure what the options are, what might how our lives might develop. Then it's very difficult to take a completely formal approach. And so I wouldn't.
POD1000000047_S0000121	trying to say, oh, we should be able to do all this mathematically at all. However, the basics of qualitative ideas of thinking through a rational decision are still very valuable because you think of, you know, what are the options available?
POD1000000047_S0000122	and what are the possibilities, and what are the possible consequences of what I might do? Now, there's always an adequate, you're never gonna be able to think of everything, however, by thinking through that, some things might become immediately apparent, some immediate rankings
POD1000000047_S0000123	what is preferable and not preferable might become apparent. And otherwise, we might need to fall back, I think, on broader strategies for making decisions in the face of
POD1000000047_S0000124	what we call deeper uncertainty. Now this is a deeply contested area. When governments make policies, very often they're in these situations where they can't even think of all the things that might happen. So they're in this situation of deeper uncertainty.
POD1000000047_S0000125	and people have suggested various ways to go about it. The first thing is not to think that you can optimize. You can't be perfect. You cannot be perfect. So the sort of suggestions that people make in terms of general decision-making in these contexts
POD1000000047_S0000126	So to do with flexibility and resilience, that you want to be, you don't want to commit yourself to something you're not going to be able to change because you can't predict everything that's going to happen. So you want to build in flexibility and adaptivity to your decision making.
POD1000000047_S0000127	And that's the same in any business, any government, any project at all. And the other thing is to build in resilience in which you essentially can cope with the unexpected and things. And that means both, you know, the possibility of really good things happening.
POD1000000047_S0000128	as well as the possibility of really bad things happening, that you are making sure that you haven't put all your eggs in one basket, essentially, so if something goes wrong, you haven't completely gone up a total blind alley that you can't renegotiate.
POD1000000047_S0000129	which means operating from the basis, most robust basis as possible. So it means not trying to optimize the single path, but building in robustness, which means, I think, in terms of career, of course, building in
POD1000000047_S0000130	transferable skills that you're going to be able to use in a variety of circumstances. So I think these are standard tactics for responding to deeper uncertainty, which can be used in any situation.
POD1000000047_S0000132	Yeah, that's definitely something that the organization 80,000 hours who advise people on, you know, how to have a big impact with their careers really focus on is especially early in your career, like keep your options open and choose things that are robust under, you know, lots of different possible things happening.
POD1000000047_S0000134	One of the question that we find we come up against a fair amount and thinking about careers and charities and all kinds of things is, you know, how do you go about choosing between a small chance of some really huge outcome like, you know, saving the world from a pandemic that kills millions?
POD1000000047_S0000136	against some high probability of a very moderate or a more moderate outcome. So, you know, helping people in your local community. This seems like a very difficult thing to deal with. Do you have any thoughts on how people can go about making these kinds of decisions?
